<section xml:id="Circles">
  <title>Circles</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Our next entry in the conic sections menagerie is the circle.
      Recall from Geometry that a circle can be determined by fixing a point
      (called the center)
      and a positive number
      (called the radius)
      as follows.
          <idx><h>circle</h><h>radius of</h></idx>
          <idx><h>circle</h><h>center of</h></idx>
          <idx><h>center</h><h>of a circle</h></idx>
          <idx><h>radius</h><h>of a circle</h></idx>
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="circledefn">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>circle</term> with center <m>(h,k)</m> and radius <m>r>0</m> is the set of all points <m>(x, y)</m> in the plane whose distance to <m>(h,k)</m> is <m>r</m>.
              <idx><h>circle</h><h>definition of</h></idx>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      \begin{mfpic}[15]{-5}{5}{-5}{5} \arrow\reverse\arrow \polyline{(0.25,0.25), (2.55,2.55)} \tlabel(-0.5,-0.8){<m>(h,k)</m>} \tlabel(1,1.55){<m>r</m>} \plotsymbol[3pt]{Cross}{(0,0)} \point[3pt]{(2.8284,2.8284)} \tlabel(3,3){<m>(x,y)</m>} \penwd{1.25pt} \circle{(0,0),4} \end{mfpic}
    </p>
    <p>
      From the diagram,
      we see that a point <m>(x,y)</m> is on the circle if and only if its distance to <m>(h,k)</m> is <m>r</m>.
      We express this relationship algebraically using the Distance Formula,
      <xref ref="distanceformula">Equation</xref>, as
      <me>
        r = \sqrt{(x - h)^2 + (y-k)^2}
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      By squaring both sides of this equation,
      we get an equivalent equation
      (since <m>r > 0</m>)
      which gives us the standard equation of a circle.
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="standardcircle">
      <title>The Standard Equation of a Circle:</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          [The Standard Equation of a Circle:] <idx><h>circle</h><h>standard equation</h></idx>
          <em>The Standard Equation of a Circle:</em>
        </p>
        <p>
          The equation of a circle with center <m>(h,k)</m> and radius <m>r >0</m> is <m>(x-h)^2 + (y-k)^2 = r^2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <p>
      Note in the standard equation of a circle,
      <em>both</em> of the variables squared.
      This is a quick way to distinguish the equation of a circle from that of a parabola in which only <em>one</em>
      of the variables is squared.
    </p>
    <p>
      We put <xref ref="standardcircle">Equation</xref>
      to good use in the following example.
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>~</m>
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="circleex1">
            <p>
              For each of the equations below:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Graph the equation in the <m>xy</m>-plane.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Find the center and radius.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(x+2)^2+(y-1)^2 = 4</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="ctscircleex">
                <p>
                  <m>3x^2 - 6x + 3y^2 + 4y -4 = 0</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Graph <m>f(x) = - \sqrt{4x-x^2}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the standard form of the circle satisfying the following characteristics:
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The points <m>(-1,3)</m> and <m>(2,4)</m> are the endpoints of a diameter.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    The circle whose graph is below. \begin{mfpic}[15]{-5}{1}{-1}{5} \axes \xmarks{-4, -3, -2, -1, 0} \ymarks{1,2,3,4} \tlabel(1,-0.5){<m>x</m>} \tlabel(0.5,5){<m>y</m>} \tlabel[cc](-2, -0.5){<m>(-2,0)</m>} \tlabel[cc](1,2){<m>(0,2)</m>} \tlpointsep{4pt} \axislabels {x}{ {<m>-4</m>} -4} \axislabels {y}{ {<m>4</m>} 4} \penwd{1.25pt} \circle{(-2,2),2} \point[4pt]{(-2,0), (0,2)} \end{mfpic}
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Rewriting <m>(x+2)^2+(y-1)^2 = 4</m> as <m>(x-(-2))^2+(y-1)^2 = (2)^2</m>,
                    we identify <m>h = -2</m>, <m>k=1</m> and <m>r = 2</m>.
                    Thus we have a circle centered at <m>(-2,1)</m> with a radius of <m>2</m>.
                    To help us create a detailed graph,
                    we start from the center <m>(-2,1)</m> and move two units to the left and two units up and down to the right to identify four points on the graph.<fn>
                    Note the center of the circle is <em>not</em>
                    on the graph of the circle!
                    </fn> We get <m>(-2-2, 1) = (-4,1)</m>, <m>(-2+2, 1) = (0,1)</m>,
                    <m>(-2, 1+2) = (-2,3)</m> and <m>(-2,1-2) = (-2,-1)</m>.
                    Our graph is below on the left.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    In order to make use of <xref ref="standardcircle">Equation</xref>,
                    we need to put <m>3x^2 - 6x + 3y^2 + 4y -4 = 0</m> into standard form.
                    To that end,
                    we complete the square on both the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> terms and collect the constants to the other side of the equation as demonstrated below.
                    <me>
                      \begin{array}{rclr} 3x^2 - 6x + 3y^2 + 4y -4 \amp  = \amp  0 \amp  \\ 3x^2 - 6x + 3y^2 + 4y \amp  = \amp  4 \amp  \text{ add \(4\) to both sides }  \\ 3\left(x^2 - 2x \right) + 3\left(y^2 + \dfrac{4}{3} y\right) \amp  = \amp  4 \amp  \text{ factor out leading coefficients }  \\ 3\left(x^2 - 2x + \underline{1} \right) + 3\left(y^2 + \dfrac{4}{3} y + \underline{\underline{\dfrac{4}{9}}} \right) \amp  = \amp  4 + 3\underline{(1)} + 3\underline{\underline{\left(\dfrac{4}{9}\right)}} \amp   \text{ complete the square in \(x\), \(y\) }  \\ 3(x - 1)^2 + 3\left(y + \dfrac{2}{3}\right)^2 \amp  = \amp  \dfrac{25}{3} \amp  \text{ factor }  \\ (x - 1)^2 + \left(y + \dfrac{2}{3}\right)^2 \amp  = \amp  \dfrac{25}{9} \amp  \text{ divide both sides by \(3\) }  \\ (x - 1)^2 + \left(y - \left(- \dfrac{2}{3} \right) \right)^2 \amp  = \amp  \left( \dfrac{5}{3} \right)^2 \amp  \text{ rewrite in the form of <xref ref="standardcircle">Equation</xref>. } \end{array}
                    </me>
                    From <xref ref="standardcircle">Equation</xref>, we identify <m>h = 1</m>,
                    <m>k =  - \frac{2}{3}</m>, and <m>r   = \frac{5}{3}</m>.
                    Hence, we have a circle with center
                    <m>\left(1, -\frac{2}{3}\right)</m> and radius  <m>\frac{5}{3}</m>.
                    As above, we find four points on the circle by starting at the center  <m>\left(1, -\frac{2}{3}\right)</m> and moving up, down,
                    to the left, and to the right <m>\frac{5}{3}</m> units.
                    Doing so produces the following points:
                    <m>\left(-\frac{2}{3}, -\frac{2}{3}\right)</m> ,
                    <m>\left(\frac{8}{3}, -\frac{2}{3}\right)</m> ,   <m>\left(1, 1\right)</m>,
                    and <m>\left(1, -\frac{7}{3}\right)</m>.
                    Our graph is below on the right.  \begin{mfpic}[20]{-5}{2}{-2}{4} \axes \plotsymbol[3pt]{Cross}{(-2,1)} \tlabel[cc](-2, 1.5){<m>(-2,1)</m>} \tlabel[cc](1, 1){<m>(0,1)</m>} \tlabel[cc](-5, 1){<m>(-4,1)</m>} \tlabel[cc](-2, 3.5){<m>(-2,3)</m>} \tlabel[cc](-2, -1.5){<m>(-2,-1)</m>} \tcaption{The graph of
                    <m>(x+2)^2+(y-1)^2 = 4</m>} \xmarks{-4, -3, -2,-1,0, 1} \ymarks{-1,0,1, 2,3} \tlabel(2,-0.25){<m>x</m>} \tlabel(0.25,4){<m>y</m>} \tlpointsep{4pt}  \axislabels {x}{{<m>-4</m>} -4, {<m>-3</m>} -3, {<m>-2</m>} -2, {<m>-1</m>} -1, {<m>1</m>} 1} \axislabels {y}{{<m>-1</m>} -1, {<m>1</m>} 1,  {<m>3</m>} 3, {<m>4</m>} 4}  \penwd{1.25pt} \circle{(-2,1),2} \point[4pt]{(0,1), (-4,1), (-2,3), (-2,-1)} \end{mfpic}  \begin{mfpic}[20]{-2}{5}{-4}{2} \axes \plotsymbol[3pt]{Cross}{(1, -0.6666)} \tlabel[cc](-1.75, -0.6666){<m>\left(-\frac{2}{3}, -\frac{2}{3}\right)</m>} \tlabel[cc](3.5, -0.6666){<m>\left(\frac{8}{3}, -\frac{2}{3}\right)</m>} \tlabel[cc](1, 1.5){<m>\left(1, 1\right)</m>} \tlabel[cc](1, -2.8){<m>\left(1, -\frac{7}{3}\right)</m>} \tlabel[cc](1, -1.25){<m>\left(1, -\frac{2}{3}\right)</m>} \tcaption{The graph of
                    <m>3x^2 - 6x + 3y^2 + 4y -4 = 0</m>} \xmarks{-1, 1, 2, 3, 4} \ymarks{-3,-2,-1,1} \tlabel(5,-0.25){<m>x</m>} \tlabel(0.25,2){<m>y</m>} \tlpointsep{4pt}  \axislabels {x}{ {<m>2</m>} 2} \axislabels {y}{{<m>-3</m>} -3,  {<m>1</m>} 1}  \penwd{1.25pt} \circle{(1,-0.6666),1.6666} \point[4pt]{(-0.6666,-0.6666), (2.6666,-0.6666), (1,1), (1,-2.3333)} \end{mfpic}
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We are asked to graph <m>f(x) = - \sqrt{4x-x^2}</m>, which,
                at first glance, seems out of place in this section.
                However, to graph means we graph the equation <m>y = -\sqrt{4x-x^2}</m>.
                Squaring both sides, we get
                <m>y^2 = (-\sqrt{4x-x^2})^2</m> or <m>y^2 = 4x - x^2</m>.
                Rearranging this equation gives <m>x^2-4x+y^2 = 0</m>.
                Completing the square, we obtain <m>(x-2)^2 + y^2 = 4</m> which,
                when rewritten as <m>(x-2)^2 + (y-0)^2 = (2)^2</m> is precisely the standard form of a circle as written in <xref ref="standardcircle">Equation</xref>.
                With <m>h = 2</m>, <m>k=0</m> and <m>r=2</m>,
                we know the graph of <m>(x-2)^2 + y^2 = 4</m> is a circle of radius <m>2</m> centered at <m>(2,0)</m>.
                However, the graph we want isn't the
                <em>entire</em> circle.<fn>
                For one thing,
                the graph of a circle fails the Vertical Line Test so it does not represent <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m> in this case.
                </fn>  Indeed, we want the graph of <m>y = -\sqrt{4x-x^2}</m>.
                Because of the <sq><m>-</m> </sq>,
                we want the <em>lower</em> semicircle,
                graphed below on the left.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    We recall that a diameter of a circle is a line segment containing the center and two points on the circle.
                    We plot the data given to us below on the right. \begin{mfpic}[20]{-2}{5}{-3}{3} \axes \plotsymbol[3pt]{Cross}{(2,0) } \tlabel[cc](2, -2.5){<m>(2,-2)</m>} \tlabel[cc](0.5, 0.25){<m>(0,0)</m>} \tlabel[cc](3.5, 0.25){<m>(4,0)</m>} \tlabel[cc](2, 0.25){<m>(2,0)</m>} \dotted \circle{(2,0),2} \tcaption{The graph of
                    <m>f(x) = - \sqrt{4x-x^2}</m>.} \xmarks{-1, 1, 3, 4} \ymarks{-2,-1,1,2} \tlabel(5,-0.25){<m>x</m>} \tlabel(0.25,3){<m>y</m>} \tlpointsep{4pt} \axislabels {x}{ {<m>1</m>} 1, {<m>2</m>} 2, {<m>3</m>} 3} \axislabels {y}{{<m>-2</m>} -2, {<m>-1</m>} -1, {<m>1</m>} 1, {<m>2</m>} 2} \penwd{1.25pt} \plrfcn{90,180,5}{4*cosd(t)} \point[4pt]{(0,0), (2,-2), (4,0)} \end{mfpic} \begin{mfpic}[20]{-2}{4}{-0.5}{5.5} \axes \dashed \circle{(0.5,3.5),3.162277660/2} \point[4pt]{(-1,3), (2,4)} \plotsymbol[3pt]{Cross}{(0.5,3.5)} \xmarks{-2,-1,0,1,2,3} \ymarks{0,1,2,3,4,5} \tlabel(4,-0.25){ <m>x</m>} \tlabel(0.25,5.5){ <m>y</m>} \arrow \reverse \arrow \polyline{(0.75,3.583),(1.75,3.916)} \tlabel[cc](0.85,3){<m>(h,k)</m>} \tlabel[cc](1.15,4){<m>r</m>} \tlpointsep{4pt} \axislabels {x}{{<m>-2</m>} -2, {<m>-1</m>} -1, {<m>1</m>} 1, {<m>2</m>} 2, {<m>3</m>} 3} \axislabels {y}{{<m>1</m>} 1, {<m>2</m>} 2, {<m>3</m>} 3, {<m>4</m>} 4, {<m>5</m>}, 5} \end{mfpic} Since the given points are endpoints of a diameter,
                    we know their midpoint <m>(h, k)</m> is the center of the circle.
                    Likewise, the diameter of the circle is the distance between the given points,
                    so we can find the radius of the circle by taking half of this distance.
                    Using <xref ref="midpointformula">Equations</xref>
                    and <xref ref="distanceformula"></xref>, respectively, we get:
                    <m>\begin{array}{rcl} (h,k) \amp = \amp \left( \dfrac{x_{\text{ \tiny\(0\) } } + x_{\text{ \tiny\(1\) } }}{2}, \dfrac{y_{\text{ \tiny\(0\) } } + y_{\text{ \tiny\(1\) } }}{2} \right) \\ \amp = \amp \left( \dfrac{-1+2}{2}, \dfrac{3+4}{2} \right) \\ \amp = \amp \left( \dfrac{1}{2}, \dfrac{7}{2} \right) \\ \amp \amp \end{array}</m> <m>\begin{array}{rcl} r \amp = \amp \dfrac{1}{2} \sqrt{\left(x_{\text{ \tiny\(1\) } } - x_{\text{ \tiny\(0\) } }\right)^2+\left(y_{\text{ \tiny\(1\) } }-y_{\text{ \tiny\(0\) } }\right)^2} \\ \amp = \amp \dfrac{1}{2} \sqrt{(2-(-1))^2+(4-3)^2} \\ \amp = \amp \dfrac{1}{2} \sqrt{3^2+1^2} \\ \amp = \amp \dfrac{\sqrt{10}}{2} \end{array}</m> Finally,
                    since <m>\left( \frac{\sqrt{10}}{2} \right)^2 = \frac{10}{4} = \frac{5}{2}</m>,
                    our answer becomes <m>\left(x - \frac{1}{2} \right)^2 + \left(y - \frac{7}{2} \right)^2 =\frac{5}{2}</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    From the graph given to us,
                    we are safe to assume the center of the circle is <m>(-2,2)</m> since the circle appears to be <em>tangent</em>
                    to the coordinate axes at <m>(-2,0)</m> and <m>(0,2)</m>.<fn>
                    Recall that for every point <m>P</m> on the circle,
                    the tangent line at <m>P</m> is perpendicular to the radial line containing the center and <m>P</m>.
                    Since the circle is tangent to the <m>x</m>-axis at <m>(-2,0)</m>,
                    the center must lie on a line perpendicular to the <m>x</m>-axis which contains <m>(-2,0)</m> or <m>x = -2</m>.
                    Likewise, the circle is tangent to the <m>y</m>-axis at <m>(0,2)</m>,
                    the center must lie on <m>y=2</m>.
                    Hence the center is <m>(-2,2)</m>.
                    </fn>  Moreover,
                    since the distance from <m>(-2,2)</m> to either of <m>(-2,0)</m> or <m>(0,2)</m> is <m>2</m>,
                    the radius of the circle is <m>2</m>.
                    Per <xref ref="standardcircle">Equation</xref>,
                    our answer is <m>(x-(-2))^2 + (y-2)^2 = (2)^2</m> or <m>(x+2)^2+(y-2)^2 = 4</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="ctscircleex">number</xref> above,
      we needed to transform a given equation into the standard form as stated in <xref ref="standardcircle">Equation</xref>.
      We record these steps below.
      Note that given an equation that represents a circle,
      <em>both</em> variables need to be squared and the squared terms must have the
      <em>same</em> coefficients.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>To Write the Equation of a Circle in Standard Form</em>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Group common variables together on one side of the equation and put the constant on the other.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Complete the square on both variables as needed.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Divide both sides by the coefficient of the squares.
            (For circles, they will be the same.)
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
      It is possible to obtain equations like
      <m>(x-3)^2 + (y+1)^2 = 0</m> or <m>(x-3)^2 + (y+1)^2 = -1</m>,
      neither of which describes a circle. (Do you see why not?) The reader is encouraged to think about what,
      if any, points lie on the graphs of these two equations.
    </p>
    <p>
      We close this section with a brief discussion of the so-called
      <em>Unit Circle</em>.<fn>
      Widely regarded as the most important circle in all of mathematics.
      </fn>
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="UnitCircle">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>Unit Circle</term> <idx><h>Unit Circle</h><h>definition of</h></idx> is the circle centered at <m>(0,0)</m> with a radius of <m>1</m>.
          The standard equation of the Unit Circle is <m>x^2 + y^2 = 1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      In some ways,
      we may think of the Unit Circle as the progenitor of all circles.
      Indeed, if we divide both sides of <xref ref="standardcircle">Equation</xref> by <m>r^2</m>,
      we obtain the alternate standard form of a circle below.
    </p>
    <proposition xml:id="standardcirclealternate">
      <title>The Alternate Standard Equation of a Circle:</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          [The Alternate Standard Equation of a Circle:] <idx><h>circle</h><h>standard equation,
          alternate</h></idx> <em>The Alternate Standard Equation of a Circle:</em>
          The equation of a circle with center <m>(h,k)</m> and radius <m>r >0</m> is
          <me>
            \dfrac{(x-h)^2}{r^2} + \dfrac{(y-k)^2}{r^2} = 1
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </proposition>
    <p>
      Taking this one step further,
      we may rewrite <xref ref="standardcirclealternate">Equation</xref> as
      <me>
        \left( \dfrac{x-h}{r} \right)^2 +  \left( \dfrac{y-k}{r} \right)^2 = 1
      </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hence, every circle can be obtained from the Unit Circle via the transformations discussed in <xref ref="Transformations">Section</xref>.<fn>
      See <xref ref="circletransunitcircleexercise">Exercise</xref>.
      </fn>
    </p>
    <p>
      Our last example has us find some important points on the the Unit Circle.
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the points on the unit circle with <m>y</m>-coordinate <m>\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Note that all points <m>(x,y)</m> on the Unit Circle satisfy the equation <m>x^2+y^2 = 1</m>.
          Hence, our first step is to replace <m>y</m> with
          <m>\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</m> and solve for <m>x</m>.
          <me>
            \begin{array}{rclr} x^2 + y^2 \amp  = \amp  1 \amp  \\ x^2 + \left(\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)^2 \amp  = \amp  1 \amp   \\ \dfrac{3}{4} + x^2 \amp  = \amp  1 \amp  \\ x^2 \amp  = \amp  \dfrac{1}{4} \amp  \\ x  \amp  = \amp  \pm \sqrt{\dfrac{1}{4}} \amp  \text{ extract square roots }  \\ x \amp  = \amp  \pm \dfrac{1}{2} \amp \end{array}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          We find <m>x = \pm \frac{1}{2}</m> so our final answers are
          <m>\left(\frac{1}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \right)</m> and <m>\left(-\frac{1}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \right)</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="ExercisesforCircles">
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="circleeqnfirst">Exercises</xref>
      - <xref ref="circleeqnlast"></xref>,
      graph the circle in the <m>xy</m>-plane.
      Find the center and radius.
      <ol cols="3">
        <li xml:id="circleeqnfirst">
          <p>
            <m>(x + 1)^{2} + (y + 5)^{2} = 100</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>(x-4)^2+(y+2)^2 = 9</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="oddcirclethree">
          <p>
            <m>\left(x + 3\right)^{2} + \left(y - \frac{7}{13}\right)^{2} = \frac{1}{4}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>(x - 5)^{2} + (y + 9)^{2} = (\ln(8))^{2}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="oddcirclefive">
          <p>
            <m>(x + e)^{2} + \left(y - \sqrt{2} \right)^{2} = \pi^{2}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li xml:id="circleeqnlast">
          <p>
            <m>\left(x - \pi \right)^{2} + \left(y - e^{2}\right)^{2} = 91^{\frac{2}{3}}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="ctscirclefirst">Exercises</xref>
      - <xref ref="ctscirclelast"></xref>,
      complete the square in order to put the equation into standard form.
      Identify the center and the radius or explain why the equation does not represent a circle.<fn>
      <ellipsis/> assuming the equation were graphed in the <m>xy</m>-plane.
      </fn>
      <ol cols="4">
        <li xml:id="ctscirclefirst">
          <p>
            <m>x^{2} - 4x + y^{2} + 10y = -25</m>
